# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **Brooklyn Atlantics** played in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished sixth in the league with a record of 22–33.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1875 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Boston Red Stockings franchise.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their fourth consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 71–8 to win the pennant by 15 games.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 62 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 54 wins.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Catcher Deacon White (.367), second baseman Ross Barnes (.364), and first baseman Cal McVey (.355) finished 1–2–3 in the league's batting race.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] McVey paced the circuit with 87 runs batted in, and outfielder Jim O'Rourke had the most home runs, with 6.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Boston offense scored more runs than any other team in the NA.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] According to the FiveThirtyEight ELO rating system, they are the greatest team of all time.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, Jim O'Rourke, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] This was the last season of the Association, which dissolved at the end of the year.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-boston-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings club would join the new National League in 1876.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **Brooklyn Atlantics** played in 1875 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished eleventh in the league with a record of 2–42.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The league folded at the conclusion of the season, and the Atlantics did not join the National League which succeeded it in 1876.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] In their second season in the National Association, the **1875 Hartford Dark Blues** finished in third place.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] They were managed by starting third baseman Bob "Death to Flying Things" Ferguson.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] The Dark Blues, with future Hall of Famer Candy Cummings, had the best pitching staff in baseball.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] Cummings won 35 games, and the 19-year-old Tommy Bond finished second in league ERA at 1.56.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-hartford-dark-blues-season] Following the season, they were one of the NA teams chosen to join the new National League.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-keokuk-westerns-season] The **Keokuk Westerns** played their first and only season of professional baseball in 1875 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-keokuk-westerns-season] They finished thirteenth in the league with a record of 1–12.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In the fall of 1874, a group of civic boosters in St.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis raised $20,000 to organize the creation of the cities first professional ball club.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings joined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1875 season and finished the season in fourth place.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They subsequently joined the new National League for the 1876 season.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The Brown Stockings joined the National League as a founding team and thus inspired what is now a rich baseball history in the city of St.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis lawyer, was named as the Brown Stockings Vice President and given the task of going east to recruit top talent.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In Brooklyn, Bishop picked up Dickey Pearce, Jack Chapman, Herman Dehlman, and Lip Pike.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In and around Philadelphia, Bishop added Ned Cuthbert, Reddy Miller, George Bradley, Bill Hague, and Joe Battin.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Dickey Pearce having been signed from the 1874 Brooklyn Atlantics became the first ever manager of the St.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Dickey Pearce is most known for his cunning managerial mind and creating the position of shortstop which he manned for the Brown Stockings in 1875.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings worst hitter—starting catcher Tom Miller—had an OPS+ of 24 over 56 games.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He hit .164—33 singles, two doubles, and one walk in 214 at-bats.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings best hitter, Lip Pike, hit .346/.352/.494, for an OPS+ of 203—74 singles, 22 doubles, 12 triples.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Lip Pike was known as the leagues most athletic hitter and for good reason as he is rumored to have raced a trotting horse and won.
[src:1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season/1875-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Eighteen-year-old Pud Galvin is credited with leading the league in ERA (1.16) while just only pitching 62 innings.
